content.description: Get your slab face on for this one.  Head out right across the runnel and then back left again. Like most routes at Doggy Dome, the crux comes early passing through the first three tightly spaced bolts. The climbing eases somewhat, and the bolting get a bit spicier. Ends at a bolted ring anchor ~ 30 meters up. A 70 meter rope works for lowering.
content.location: Starts just right Living Water/Munter Bitch.

content.description: If the OW is getting old (not everyone's cup of tea), you can "stray" off to the right to a bolt and then past 3 more to bolted anchors.
content.protection: A couple 4" pieces for OW and then 4 draws for bolts.
content.location: Start on Doggy Style and move right at the ledge past the 4 bolts.

content.description: Clip the first bolt, pull on some slopers and paddle up the slab until it steepens. A mantel is followed by some tricky face climbing. Head left to the anchor of "Two Right Shoes". Lower off with a single 70m rope.
content.location: The next water runnel/streak to the right of "Two Right Shoes"

climbs.name: Sexy Bitch
climbs.fa: Dec. 4, 2021 Matt Schutz and Tom Slater

content.description: Climb up the right side of Dogtown slab past the first two bolts and then veer left. Do some more sustained friction climbing past several more bolts until the features begin to grow as the terrain steepens. Chain anchor on top. Starts with friction, then small edges, then bigger edges, then small knobs, then horns. A beautiful slab line.
content.location: Dogtown Slab wasn't developed until almost 10 years after the first routes were done at Doggy Dome. It was hiding in plain sight around the corner. Thus, these routes are not part of the main wall, they are climber's left from the main dome. The new trail pretty much leads right up to it. Cross the fallen logs to the base.

climbs.name: Runaway
climbs.fa: FTR Tom Slater (solo mini-traxion/equipped with 6 bolts) January 2012. FFA Jeremy Ross Sept. 2012

content.description: The start is the same as Dogs of War but then heads up right to slashes/gashes then up featured face past 3 more bolts. Gear needed for deep slashes. I found this route just a tad easier than Dogs of War, but they both share the difficult thin entry moves so they're the same grade. Just didn't seem as sustained.
content.protection: 6 draws, gear to 3". Chain anchor for both Dogs and Runaway.
content.location: Shares the start of Dogs of War, then turns trad, then back to bolts. A straight up line.

content.description: A fun and sustained face route.

climbs.name: Lords of Dogtown
climbs.fa: Dec. 4, 2021 Tom Slater & Matt Schutz on lead on sight

content.description: Start on the right side of Dogtown Slab and friction climb straight up and then slightly right towards the arete. Follow a line of 6 bolts up to the "spur" where the knobs and horns begin. You can sling a knob, or cam a joint, or use a nut here. Then climb up beautiful knobs and plates into steeper terrain past two more bolts (and another possible knob sling) to chain anchors (the two routes on this wall share the same anchor on top - rings). The friction climbing is sustained but yields at the "spur" and then turns into a ridiculously fun knob climbing adventure.
content.protection: 8 draws and two knob slings (or small cam/large nut)
content.location: Dogtown Slab is 250' left of the main wall. From the new trail up the hillside, continue straight up to the wall and walk across 2 large downed dead trees (like a bridge over the brush). There is a clearing just below the slab. From here, you can access the main wall by heading right up and over the hump contouring the base of the main formation.

content.description: An excellent and easy route up classic Shuteye  water runnels with plates and knobs.
content.protection: A 3” cam at the start, then 4 bolts mixed with a sling leads to chain anchors.
content.location: Starts on the low angle ramp on the far right side of the dome. Shares the same start as Munter Bitch.

climbs.name: God’s Eye View
climbs.fa: Tom Slater, Coby Whitaker and the Ross brothers

content.description: A stiff start leads to excellent and featured climbing above.

climbs.name: Dogs of War
climbs.fa: FTR Tom Slater (solo mini-traxion/equipped with 11 bolts) January 2012. FFA Jeremy Ross Sept. 2012

content.description: Start on the thin face to the right of Doggy Style OW. Crux is the bottom of the route. Then ascend a very steep featured face (knobs and a water runnel) to the top.
content.location: Look for the bolts on the thin face to the right of Doggy Style OW. Runaway shares the same start.

climbs.name: Doggy Style
climbs.fa: FA Tom Slater  Jan 2012 (possibly done before since it's an obvious OW but no record exists).

content.description: The most obvious line at the crag. An OW from top to bottom. Bolted anchors on top below the summit blocks.
content.location: You can't miss it. The only OW on the wall. Left of center.

climbs.name: A Little Humpy
climbs.fa: FA Grahm Doe, Tom Slater, Leo Miner Feb 2012

content.description: A sport route that follows thin water runnels and "humps".
content.location: The face to the right of God's Eye View.
